From 07a24f4927591e5770cdc41b896b16bf3f8699d2 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nick <mermiges@gmail.com>
Date: Tue, 7 Jul 2026 05:32:17 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 1/2] deepseek4 : make attention rotation-aware (raw + sparse
 paths)

Teach DeepSeek-V4's attention builders to apply and undo the block-Hadamard
incoherence rotation, so a quantized K-cache can keep the rotation enabled
instead of being force-disabled for the arch.

Background: a quantized K/V cache enables the Hadamard rotation (self_k_rot).
The raw/CSA/HCA K-caches all use the 576-wide MLA head (nrot = 64, a shared
symmetric-involution Hadamard); the lightning indexer uses its own 128-block
rotation and was already correct.

- Add a file-local ggml_mul_mat_aux helper (block semantics: reshape dim-0 into
  nrot-wide blocks, apply the nrot x nrot matrix per block, restore shape),
  mirroring the helpers in llama-graph.cpp / llama-kv-cache.cpp. A plain
  ggml_mul_mat(64x64, 576-wide) is a shape error and does not rotate.

- build_raw_attention (option c): rotate Q and K with ggml_mul_mat_aux instead
  of the broken plain ggml_mul_mat, and un-rotate the P*V output before it is
  de-roped and fed to the output projection (V is the same rotated K, so its
  rotation is self_k_rot; the matrix is an involution so the same call undoes it).

- build_csa_lid_attention / build_hca_attention (option b): drop the
  self_k_rot==nullptr asserts; rotate Q and the raw K stored to the raw cache,
  and un-rotate the attention output. build_attention writes a rotated copy of
  the compressed CSA/HCA K to those caches (the compressor STATE stays
  un-rotated). All caches share the same 64-block matrix, so one self_k_rot
  rotates Q and every K consistently; K.Q is preserved and O = R*O_unrot is
  undone by another R. Compression is linear, so rotating the compressed K
  equals compressing rotated K.

- Dispatch: remove the self_k_rot==nullptr guards so quantized-K CSA/HCA layers
  stay on their trained sparse paths instead of diverting to dense
  build_raw_attention.

Verified: q8_0-K coherent at temp 0 on all four KV-type combinations (rotation
on), matching the f16-K and rotation-off controls; CSA/HCA layers run ~6x faster
than the dense fallback, confirming the sparse paths are taken with rotation on.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 src/models/deepseek4.cpp | 104 +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++----
 1 file changed, 94 insertions(+), 10 deletions(-)

diff --git a/src/models/deepseek4.cpp b/src/models/deepseek4.cpp
index 759654228..d66e509c2 100644
--- a/src/models/deepseek4.cpp
+++ b/src/models/deepseek4.cpp
@@ -15,6 +15,36 @@ static float dsv4_rope_attn_factor(float freq_scale, float ext_factor) {
     return 1.0f / (1.0f + 0.1f*logf(1.0f/freq_scale));
 }
 
+// Apply a block-diagonal (Hadamard incoherence) rotation to a tensor whose
+// dim-0 is a multiple of the rotation width n = rot->ne[0]. The tensor is
+// reshaped into n-wide blocks, the n x n matrix is applied to every block, and
+// the original shape is restored. This is the block semantics the standard
+// (llama-graph.cpp) attention path uses for self_k_rot/self_v_rot; DeepSeek-V4's
+// attention builders need the SAME semantics (a plain ggml_mul_mat would demand
+// rot->ne[0] == cur->ne[0], which is false for the 576-wide MLA head and a 64
+// rotation block). rot is a symmetric involution (rot*rot == I), so the same
+// call un-rotates an attention output. Mirrors the file-local helpers in
+// llama-graph.cpp and llama-kv-cache.cpp.
+static ggml_tensor * ggml_mul_mat_aux(
+        ggml_context * ctx,
+        ggml_tensor * cur,
+        ggml_tensor * rot) {
+    const auto n = rot->ne[0];
+
+    ggml_tensor * res;
+
+    if (!ggml_is_contiguous(cur)) {
+        res = ggml_cont_2d   (ctx, cur, n, ggml_nelements(cur)/n);
+    } else {
+        res = ggml_reshape_2d(ctx, cur, n, ggml_nelements(cur)/n);
+    }
+    res = ggml_mul_mat   (ctx, rot, res);
+    ggml_mul_mat_set_hint(res, GGML_HINT_SRC0_IS_HADAMARD);
+    res = ggml_reshape_4d(ctx, res, cur->ne[0], cur->ne[1], cur->ne[2], cur->ne[3]);
+
+    return res;
+}
